******
[2]
Date: Sun 7 Oct 2018 14:59 CEST
Source: Belga via Sudinfo (Belgium) [in French, machine trans., edited]
https://www.sudinfo.be/id78653/article/2018-10-07/peste-porcine-africaine-dallemagne-veut-des-precisions-de-vandeput-sur-les


Federal MP [member of parliament] Georges Dallemagne (cdH [Humanist Democratic Centre party]) will soon be questioning Defense Minister Steven Vandeput (N-VA [New Flemish Alliance party]) in the House about the discovery of several cadavers of wild boars, one of which has been tested positive for the African swine fever virus, in the Lagland military camp in the province of Luxembourg.

In particular, Mr Dallemagne wishes to obtain details on the number of cadavers found, as well as on the timing of the discoveries and the way in which the information was processed.

He will also ask the Minister for clarification regarding the participation of Belgian troops in exercises abroad, in areas infected by the virus, or the training of foreign troops on Belgian soil.

"Is there any exchange between the staff of the different infected countries? Has training been given? Are our soldiers and those in the countries concerned aware of the means of propagation of the virus and basic measures of biosecurity?" asks the humanist MP, who considers it "urgent to have answers to these questions".

According to him, the measures taken by the Walloon Minister of Agriculture, his party colleague Ren√© Collin, "are good, but cannot be the only ones." He insists that "the other departments are equally mobilized."

The Lagland military camp is located in the 63 000 hectares [about 156 000 acres] of forest affected by the movement ban within the framework of the management of ASF.

