[A map showing the location of the Lagland military camp is available at http://wikimapia.org/7217894/Camp-Lagland. The following information on the camp is derived from the official Belgian Ministry of Defence website "Defensie" (https://www.mil.be/nl/eenheden/kamp-lagland; in Dutch, trans. Mod.AS):

"In the Camp Lagland, 80 military personnel work to offer training infrastructure to combat and reconnaissance troops.
The camp is located in the far south of Belgium, near the city of Arlon, and covers an area of 2600 hectares [about 6425 acres]. Nearby are also the Infantry Department and the Center for Basic Training and South Schooling.

"Camp Lagland is a national competence center for training in military operations in built-up areas. For this the soldiers built the artificial village of Asperulange, which consists of about 40 houses. The camp has numerous shooting ranges and extensive practice areas for tactical training.

"Because of the risks of regular target practice, access to the military site is forbidden for all citizens. Due to its great diversity of fauna and flora, the entire camp is completely in the protected nature zone 'Natura 2000'.
Only in exceptional cases can the camp commander grant derogations, for youth movements, scientific research, or exceptional sports activities.

"Camp Lagland puts 2 bivouac zones (for 60 or 200 people) at the disposal of recognized youth movements. Because the military domain remains open as a training ground, both zones are only accessible during the Easter holidays (one week) and in August".

According to a later report in 'De Standaard', dated 7 Oct 2018, Belgium's Federal Food Agency (FASFC) considers that the theory of Belgian soldiers introducing the ASF virus after operations in the Baltic countries is "unlikely". "'Defense uses strict decontamination procedures', says Philippe Houdart of the FASFC. 'It is more likely that an Eastern European van was throwing its roll of contaminated salami into a parking lot and that was eaten by wild boars here.'" The FASFC's comment did not address the scenario of foreign soldiers training in Lagland.

The response further says, that 4 wild boar cadavers were found in the camp, of which 2 were found infected. After the diagnosis, "Lagland's military training area, near Arlon, has been stationary for 3 weeks. The camp is threatened with a closure of several months to a year." (http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20181007_03817143; in Dutch, trans. Mod.AS).

According to the FASFC's website, updated 8 Oct 2018, the number of wild boar confirmed as infected in Belgium's SE province Luxembourg since 13 Sep 2018, has risen to 53. - Mod.AS

